<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-debugging" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Debugging</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        What do you do when R code throws an unexpected error? What tools do
        you have to find and fix the problem? This chapter will teach you the
        art and science of debugging.
      </p>

      <p>
        A typo in the code, an unexpected input, and many other problems will
        cause code to fail. In many languages, even the simplest mistakes will
        cause the program to terminate. In R, the interactivity of the language
        means that you're usually in a better position: even when errors occur
        you can often figure out what went wrong.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="sec-overall-approach">
      <title>Overall approach</title>

      <p>
        Finding your bug is a process of confirming the many things that you
        believe are true, until you find one that is not true. When a bug
        bites, I recommend a three-step approach to find it:
      </p>

      <p><ol>
        <li><p>
          Google: whenever you see an error message, start by googling it.
          If you're lucky, you'll discover that it's a known bug with a known
          solution.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          Make it repeatable: to find the root cause of an error, you need to
          be able to repeat it on command.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          Figure out where it is: once you can make the bug happen reliably,
          the next step is to figure out where it comes from.
        </p></li>
      </ol></p>
    </section>

  </chapter>
